@node P1Polynomials "P1: Algebraic Processing Skills - Polynomials"
@{u}Polynomials@{uu}

A polynomial is an algebraic expression that is a sum of a number of terms.
    eg. 2x³ + 5x² + 6x + 1

The degree of a polynomial is the highest power of x (example above is degree 3)

The most number of terms in an equation is [degree+1]
@endnode

@node P1PolynomialsAdd "P1: Algebraic Processing Skills - Adding & Subtracting Polynomials"
@{u}Adding and Subtracting Polynomials@{uu}

When adding or subtracting polynomials, only like terms can be combined.

eg. (3x²+2x+5)+(6x³+x+7) = 6x³+3x²+3x+12
@endnode

@node P1PolynomialsMulti "P1: Algebraic Processing Skills - Multiplying Polynomials"
@{u}Multiplying Polynomials@{uu}

When multiplying polynomials, add the indices

eg. (6x²+2x-3)(2x-4)
  = 12x³-24x²+4x²-8x-6x+12
  = 12x³-20x²-14x+12
@endnode

@node P1PolynomialsFactor "P1: Algebraic Processing Skills - Factorising Polynomials"
@{u}Factorising Polynomials@{uu}

When two expressions are equal for all values of x, the symbol '@{u}=@{uu}' (three parallel lines) should be used.  It is an @{"identity" link P2AlgebraIdentities}.

Commonly occuring identities:

(x+y)²     = x²+2xy+y²
(x-y)²     = x²-2xy+y²
(x-y)(x+y) = x²-y²
(x+y)³     = x³+3x²y+3xy²+y³
(x-y)³     = x³-3x²y+3xy²-y³

To factorise, take out a common factor:

eg. 3x+6 = 3(x+2)

When working with trinomials, you must factorise into 2 brackets:

eg. x²-8x+16 = (x-4)(x-4)

or the longer way:

for an equation ax²+bx+c=0, find two factors of ac which add up to give b.  The bx part of the equation can then be rewritten:

2x²+4x-6=0

Two factors of 2 and -6: -2 and 6

2x²-2x+6x-6=0

Factorise in pairs:

2x(x-1)+6(x-1)=0   »»» THE BRACKETS MUST BE THE SAME «««

Take everything outside into one bracket, and inside into another:

(2x+6)(x-1)=0
@endnode

