@node P1EquationSim "P1: Equations and Inequalities - Solving Simultaneous Equations"
@{u}Solving Simultaneous Equations@{uu}

To solve simultaneous equations, you can use three different methods:

@{"Draw a graph" link P1EquationSimGraph}
@{"Elimination " link P1EquationSimElim}
@{"Substitution" link P1EquationSimSub}
@endnode

@node P1EquationSimGraph "P1: Equations and Inequalities - Simultaneous Equations"
@{u}Solving Simultaneous Equations Graphically@{uu}

Draw graphs accurately, writing down where they cross.
@endnode

@node P1EquationSimElim "P1: Equations and Inequalities - Simultaneous Equations"
@{u}Solving Simultaneous Equations By Elimination@{uu}

Cancel out one of the unknowns by subtracting one equation from the other.

eg. 2x+3y=9   [Eq1]
    4x+9y=12  [Eq2]

Eq1 × 2: 4x+6y=18  [Eq3]

Eq2-Eq3: 3y=-6
          y=-2

Then @{"substitute" link P1EquationSimSub y into the other equation.
@endnode

@node P1EquationSimSub "P1: Equations and Inequalities - Simultaneous Equations"
@{u}Solving Simultaneous Equations By Substitution@{uu}

Rearrange one equation, then substitute it into the other one:

eg. 7x-9y=4 [Eq1]
      x+y=1 [Eq2]

Rearrange Eq2:     x=1-y

Substitute in Eq1: 7(1-y)-9y=4
                     7-7y-9y=4
                       7-16y=4
                           7=4+16y
                           3=16y
@{i}                           y=3/16@{ui}

Substitute y in one of the above equations:

                           x=1-(3/16)
                           x=@{u}13@{uu}
                             16
@endnode

@node P1EquationQuad "P1: Equations and Inequalities - Quadratic Equations"
@{u}Solving Quadratic Equations@{uu}

First make sure that the equation is in the form:

    ax²+bx+c=0

You can then use one of the following methods:

@{"Factorisation        " link P1EquationQuadFactor}
@{"Equation             " link P1EquationQuadEquation}
@{"Completing the Square" link P1EquationQuadSquare}
@endnode

@node P1EquationQuadFactor "P1: Equations and Inequalities - Quadratic Equations"
@{u}Solving Quadratic Equations by Factorisation@{uu}

First @{"factorise" link P1PolynomialsFactor} the equation, then make the first and second brackets equal to 0:

eg. (x-7)(x+2)=0

    x=7 or x=-2

IT IS NOT POSSIBLE TO FACTORISE ALL QUADRATICS
@endnode

@node P1EquationQuadEquation "P1: Equations and Inequalities - Quadratic Equations"
@{u}Solving Quadratic Equations using the quadratic formulae@{uu}

Where ax²+bx+c=0, you can use the equation:

@{fg shine}x = @{u}-b ± ð(b²-4ac)@{uu}
            2a@{fg text}

b²-4ac is called the discriminant.

If b²-4ac=0, there is only one solution.
If b²-4ac>0, two solutions
If b²-4ac<0, no (real) solutions
If b²-4ac is a perfect square, the equation will factorise
@endnode

@node P1EquationQuadSquare "P1: Equations and Inequalities - Quadratic Equations"
@{u}Solving Quadratic Equations by Completing the Square@{uu}

x²+6x-12=0

take the "+c" part of the equation over to the other side:

x²+6x=+12

Simplify the equation so the first term is just x² (if needed)

Write the first side as a square.  The second number in the bracket is ½ of the "bx" term:

(x+3)²=12

This is not true.  To make the equation correct you must add the square of the number in the bracket to the second side:

(x+3)²=12+9

(x+3)²=21
   x+3=±ð(21)-3

x=-ð(21)-3 or x=ð(21)-3
@endnode

