@node P1InEqualGraph "P1: Equations and Inequalities - Quadratic Inequalities"
@{u}Solving Quadratic Inequalities Graphically@{uu}

Find the critical values by making ax²+bx+c=0.  This can be done by @{"solving" link P1EquationQuad} the equation.  The critical values show where the line crosses the x-axis.

The line crosses the y-axis at the "+c" value of the equation.

You can now @{"sketch" link P1FunctionsSketch} the curve and check to see which values of x satisfy the equation. (cr1<x<cr2 or x<cr1, x>cr2).

Alternatively, substitute numbers between and outside the critical values of x to check whether they satisfy the equation.
@endnode

@node P1InEqualTable "P1: Equations and Ineqaulities - Quadratic Inequalities"
@{u}Solving Quadratic Inequalities using a table@{uu}

Find the critical values by making the equation equal to 0, then @{"solving" link P1EquationQuad}.

You must @{"factorise" link P1PolynomialsFactor} the equation.

Complete the table below, where C1 is critical value 1 and C2 is critical value 2 for the equation (B1)(B2)=0.  Check values of x and write whether they are positive or negative underneath.  In the last column multiply the first two columns together.

@{u}        |  <C1  |C1<x<C2|  >C2  |
  (B1)  |   ±   |   ±   |   ±   |
  (B2)  |   ±   |   ±   |   ±   |
(B1)(B2)|   ±   |   ±   |   ±   |@{uu}

The last column shows which range of values satisfy the equation (x<C1 or x>C2, C1<x<C2).
@endnode

@node P1Functions "P1: Functions"
@{u}Functions@{uu}

A function is a mapping between two variables, usually:

x: the independent variable
y: the dependent variable

The range of values taken by x is called the domain, and the range of values for y is called the range.

Functions are written:

f: x -> y     or     y = f(x)

y=f(x) is often called the cartesian equation of the function.

All symbols below should be double-lined:

Z: The set of integers
N: The set of natural numbers (positive integers)
Q: The set of @{"rational" link P1Surds} numbers
R: The set of real numbers
@endnode

@node P1FunctionsComp "P1: Functions"
@{u}Composite Functions@{uu}

f: x -> 2x  g: x -> x-3

fg: x -> 2(x-3)
gf: x -> 2x-3
ff: x -> 4x
gg: x -> x-6

In forming composite functions gf(x).  Remember that, in general, fg(x) <> gf(x).
@endnode

@node P1FunctionsInverse "P1: Functions - Inverse Functions"
@{u}Inverse Functions@{uu}

f:   x -> x+2
f-¹: x -> x-2

For a one-one function f, the inverse function f-¹ exists and ff-¹(x) = f-¹f(x) = x.

The inverse of a function f is the function that undoes f.

The graph of a function and its inverse are reflected in the line y=x.

If a function and its inverse are the same, the function is self-inverse (-x and /x functions are self inverse):

f(x)   = 4/x        f(x)   = 3-x
f-¹(x) = 4/x        f-¹(x) = 3-x
@endnode

@node P1FunctionsMod "P1: Functions"
@{u}The Modulus Function@{uu}

y=|x|

The modulus of a number is the number (size) without a sign attached.  ie. The positive square root of the square of the number +ð(x²).

eg. |-5| = 5

Graphs of modulus functions reflect in the line y=0.
@endnode

@node P1FunctionsSketch "P1: Functions - Graphs"
@{u}Symmetry in Graphs@{uu}

If f(x) = f(-x), then it is an even function.

Even functions are symmetrical along the y-axis (x=0) eg. y=x²

If f(x) = -f(-x), then it is an odd function.

Odd functions have rotational symmetry.  eg. y=x³
@endnode

@node P1FunctionsTransform "P1: Functions - Graphs"
@{u}Transforming Graphs@{uu}

@{i}@{"1. y=f(x)   y=af(x)" system Multiview P1_TF1}@{ui}

Points on the x-axis remain unchanged.  All other points are @{b}a@{ub} times their original value in the y-direction.

@{i}@{"2. y=f(x)   y=f(ax)" system Multiview P1_TF4}@{ui}

Points on the y-axis remain unchanged, all other points are compacted by a factor of @{b}a@{ub} in the x-direction.

@{i}@{"3. y=f(x)   y=f(x)+a" system Multiview P1_TF2}@{ui}

The transformation translates the graph @{b}a@{ub} in the y-direction.

@{i}@{"4. y=f(x)   y=f(x+a)" system Multiview P1_TF3}@{ui}

The transformation translates the curve @{b}a@{ub} in the opposite x-direction.
@endnode

