If you have more than one force, you can draw all the forces on a diagram.
You can then work out the components of all the forces and add them up in each direction.  Remember when adding up and down forces, the down forces must be negative.  Same with left and right.
@endnode

@node M1Equil "M1: Equilibrium"
@{u}Objects in Equilibrium@{uu}

When an object is in equlibrium the resultant of all the forces acting on it is 0.  If we choose two perpendicular directions, the @{"components" link M1Comp} in each of the directions will total 0.  If we draw a polygon of forces for an object in equilibrium, the polygon joins up.
@endnode

@node M1Forces "M1: Types of Forces"
@{u}Types of Forces@{uu}

@{b}Weight@{ub} is the force tht is produced by the pull of the Earth on an object.  We calculate weight by using:

» Weight = mass × acceleration due to gravity

On Earth the acceleration due to gravity is 9.81 m/s², which is sometimes taken as 9.8 m/s² or 10 m/s².

@{b}@{"Tension" link M1Pulley}@{ub}

An object is under tension when under the action of pulling forces.
We shall come across tension in taut strings.

@{b}@{"Thrust" link M1Connect}@{ub}

An object is experiencing a thrust when pushing forces are acting on it.

@{b}@{"Normal Reaction" link M1Friction}@{ub}

The normal reaction force come into play when an object is in contact with the surface.  This reaction is always at right-angles to the surface.

@{b}@{"Friction" link M1Friction}@{ub}

Friction arises when an object is trying to move while still being in contact with a rough surface.

Friction force always opposes the tendency to motion and in some cases is great enough to stop the motion.
@endnode

@node M1Friction "M1: Friction"
@{u}Friction@{uu}

Friction occurs between rough surfaces.  If the surfaces are smooth then f=0.  If forces are acting to cause movement between the two surfaces which are in contact, then friction is called into play.  Friction always opposes this motion.

Friction is a variable force which can increase up to a maximum value which we call limiting friction.

When friction is limiting Fmax = µR
Where R is the normal reaction and µ the coefficient of friction.  µ is constant for two given surfaces.
@endnode

@node M1AccelF "M1: Accelerating Force"
@{u}Accelerating Force@{uu}

The accelerating force equation is:

» Accelerating Force = mass × acceleration... F=ma
@endnode

@node M1Pulley "M1: Pulley Systems"
@{u}Pulley Systems@{uu}

Smooth Pulley => No @{"Friction" link M1Friction}

For pulley systems we use the accelerating force @{"equation" link M1AccelF}:

To find tension and acceleration we consider which direction the masses are going to move when the system is released from rest.

Mass moving down: mg-T = ma
Mass moving up:   T-mg = ma
@endnode

