@node T1Intro "Statistics 1: Introduction & Definitions"
@{u}Introdution@{uu}

A @{i}statistic@{ui} is a number which has some relevance to data that is being studied.  For example, the mean is a statistic.
A @{i}continous variate@{ui} is one which can take any value in a given range. eg. height, weight, time waiting for a bus.
A @{i}discrete variate@{ui} is one which can only take specific values. eg. show size, clothes size, colour of eyes.
@{i}Quantitative data@{ui} is given in the form of a number (quantity).  It is usually measured.
@{i}Qualitative data@{ui} involves a description eg. type of book, colour of hair.
The words used to describe qualitative data are called @{i}non-numeric descriptors@{ui}
@endnode

