@node T1SamplingDefn "T1: Sampling/Definitions"
@{u}Sampling Definitions@{uu}

A @{i}sample@{ui} is a small group taken from a larger one.  If the large group involves all the people/items that have to be considered in a survey, then the large group is called the @{i}population@{ui}.
You can have a @{i}finite@{ui} population eg. pupils in a school, or you can have an @{i}infinite population@{ui} (unknown number).
You can have a @{i}countably infinite population@{ui}, if you are able to order the data.
A @{i}sampling frame@{ui} is a list of all members of the population being studied.  It is important to choose the sampling frame carefully to avoid any bias in the results of a survey.
A @{i}sampling unit@{ui} is an individual member chosen from the sampling frame.
A sampling unit may not be one person or item. eg. it could be a family.  If a sampling unit has several members, each member is called a @{i}sampling element@{ui}.
@endnode

@node T1SamplingBias "T1: Sampling/Bias"
@{u}Bias in Samples@{uu}

In many populations, there will be natural variations.  It is important when choosing a sampling frame to bear in mind any natural variation that is relevant to a particular survey and to ensure that the sampling frame covers all aspects of this natural variation.  If not, the sample could be biased.

Other ways in which the sample could be biased are:

1. Imposing a subjective opinion when setting up a survey
2. If a postal questionnaire was sent out, there will be a group of people who do not respond.  You need to consider the reasons for this non-response to check if it brings bias into the results.
3. It is important to put impartial questions in questionnaires to avoid bias.
@endnode

