@node T1Mode "T1: Summarising sample data: Measures of location - Mode"
@{u}The Mode@{uu}

The mode is the value of the variate which occurs most frequently.  Data can have more than one mode; it can be bi-modal, tri-modal, multi-modal...
If data is grouped, there will be a modal class.
@endnode

@node T1Median "T1: Summary: Location - Median"
@{u}The Median@{uu}

The median is the middle value of an ordered set of data.  If there are n items of data ordered, then the median is the (n+1)÷2 th item.

For grouped data: The median should be at the (n+1)÷2 th item.  But, because with grouped data, n is large and we have already introduced inaccuracies by grouping the data, we take the approximation (n+1)÷2 = n÷2.

The median can also be calculated using the formula:

MEDIAN = b+[(½n-f)÷fc]×c

where, b = lower class boundary
       c = class width
       n = number of terms
       f = total frequency -> lower class boundary
       fc= frequency for median class
@endnode

@node T1Quartiles "T1: Summarising Data - Quartiles"
@{u}Quartiles@{uu}

Quartiles occur ¼ and ¾ of the way through a set of ordered data.
The lower quartile Q1 is at ¼(n+1) or ¼n for grouped data.
The upper quartile, Q3 is at ¾(n+1) or ¾n.
@endnode

@node T1Deciles "T1: Summarising Data - Deciles"
@{u}Deciles@{uu}

These are the same as @{"quartiles" link T1Quartiles}, but occur at ¹/10, ²/10, ³/10 etc. through a set of ordered data

1st decile D1 is at (n+1)÷10 or n÷10 for grouped data.
2nd decile D2 is at 2(n+1)÷10 or 2n÷10 for grouped data.
@endnode

@node T1Percentiles "T1: Summarising Data - Percentiles"
@{u}Percentiles@{uu}

These are the same as @{"quartiles" link T1Quartiles}, but occur at ¹/100 (1%), ²/100 (2%), ³/100 (3%) etc. through a set of ordered data

1st percentile P1 is at (n+1)÷100 or n÷100 for grouped data.
2nd percentile P2 is at 2(n+1)÷100 or 2n÷100 for grouped data.
@endnode

