@node T1Dispersion "T1: Measures Of Dispersion"
@{u}Measures of Dispersion@{uu}

The mean on its own only gives a limited impression of the data under consideration.

For example, if these pupils took a series of four tests, producing these results:

                    A  B
                    -  -
                    5  0
                    5  6
                    5  4
                    5  10

We can see that they both have the same mean of 5, but pupil A is more consistent.  To measure this consistency, we have to look at a measure of dispersion or spread, such as the range.  For A, range = 0.  For B, range = 10.  The greater the measure of spread, the less consistent or reliable the results are.

@{"Range                      " link T1Range}
@{"Interquartile Range        " link T1IQRange}
@{"Variance/Standard Deviation" link T1SD}
@endnode

@node T1Range "T1: Measures of dispersion - Range"
@{u}Range@{uu}

@{i}Range = highest result - lowest result@{ui}

This is a very rough measure of spread, and is affected by freak results at the upper and lower end.
@endnode

@node T1IQRange "T1: Measures of dispersion - Interquartile Range"
@{u}Interquartile Range@{uu}

@{I}Interquartile range = @{"upper quartile" link T1Quartiles} (Q3) - @{"lower quartile" link T1Quartiles} (Q1)@{ui}

This is a measure of spread about the median.

@{i}Semi-interquartile range = @{u}Q3 - Q1@{uu}
                                  2
@endnode

@node T1SD "T1: Measures of dispersion - Variance and Standard Deviation"
@{u}Variance and Standard Deviation@{uu}
_
x = sample mean     µ = population mean

Variance and standard deviation are measures of dispersion about the mean.  x - µ is the deviation of an individual score from the mean.  This is squared to overcome the problem of minus signs.  We then take the mean of these squared deviations to get the variance, and the standard deviation is the square root of the variance.

For individual items of data:

(Z is supposed to be a summation sign)

variance = @{u}Z(x-µ)²@{uu}
              n

standard deviation = ð[@{u}Z(x-µ)²@{uu}]
                          n

For grouped data:

variance = @{u}Zf(x-µ)²@{uu}
              Zf

standard deviation = ð[@{u}Zf(x-µ)²@{uu}]
                          Zf


Alternative formulae:

Variance = @{u}Zx²@{uu} - µ²                     Variance = @{u}Zfx²@{uu} - µ²
            n                                       Zf

Standard deviation = ðvariance

